==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} < {{etyl|xno}} < {{etyl|la}} {{term|argumentum||proof, evidence, token, subject, contents}} <  {{term|arguere||to prove, argue}}; see [[argue]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈɑːgjʊmənt/}}, {{SAMPA|/"A:gjUm@nt/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈɑɹgjumənt/}}, {{SAMPA|/"Ar\gjum@nt/}}
* {{audio|en-us-argument.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[fact]] or [[statement]] used to [[support]] a [[proposition]]; <span id="N1">a [[reason]]</span>:
# <span id="N2">A verbal [[dispute]]; a [[quarrel]].</span>
# <span id="N3">A [[process]] of [[reasoning]].</span>
# <span id="N4">{{context|philosophy|logic}}</span> A [[series]] of [[statements]] [[organize]]d so that the [[final]] statement is a [[conclusion]] which is [[intend]]ed to [[follow]] [[logically]] from the [[preceding]] statements, which function as [[premise]]s.
# <span id="N5">{{math}} The independent variable of a function.</span>
# <span id="N6">{{programming}} A [[value]]</span>, or reference to a value, passed to a [[function]].  <!-- call by value v.s. call by reference -->
# <span id="N7">{{programming}} A [[parameter]]</span> in a function definition; a [[formal argument]].
# A summary or short statement of the plot or <span id="N8">chief points of  a book.</span>

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|formal parameter in a function definition}} Some authors regard use of "argument" to mean "formal parameter" to be imprecise, preferring that ''argument'' refers only to the value that is used to instantiate the ''parameter'' at runtime, while ''parameter'' refers only to the name in the function definition that will be instantiated.

